product_title: Bluetooth Speakers Dylan™ Cocoon Portable Bluetooth Speakers with Nfc, Wireless Speaker System / Portable Speakers with 1800mah Li-ion Battery, Ultra Bass Booster, Powerful Crystal-clear Sound, Subwoofer Sound Effect / Built in Mic for Calls / for Smart Phones and Tablets / Laptops / Pc Computers / Mp3 Players (Silver)
review_body:
The connection on my iHOME cube was beginning to cut out. It had been worth every penny; I used it daily at work. But when looking to replace it with another cube, the comments by Amazon customers on the Dylan COCOON really caught my eye. I am not an audiophile but have been listening to music since the mid-50's. I hooked this up to my Sandisk Sansa Clip and tried it with Blues, Rock, Jazz, Classical, Techno, Lounge Music, Funk and R&B. Whoa! This won't fill a room like my Bowers & Wilkins speakers; that isn't what it is for. But I'm tellin' you it has way more range than you would expect from this little unit. Plenty of highs when listening to Al DiMeola's guitar and easily enough bass for Parliament Funkadelic. (I can imagine Billy Mays shouting Oxy-Clean through this thing.) Some customers complain that the connecting cord for recharging is too short, and for many that may be so. But I'm betting that those same customers already have several of those if they have ever replaced a phone, tablet, mp3 player and the like, to so me that should not be a big deal. What is a big deal is the sound quality the COCOON provides. WOOT! I do not have blue tooth (My phone is not smart) so I connect via the 2nd accessory cable and am totally happy with that arrangement.
In advance, I'd like to say I hope you enjoy your Dylan COCOON!

product_title: Senbowe™Waterproof Bluetooth 3.0 Wireless Stereo Bluetooth Speaker /Wireless Outdoor Speaker/Shower Speaker with Handsfree,Control Buttons,Dedicated Removable Suction Cup for Showers, Bathroom, Pool, Boat, Car, Beach,Compatible for Apple iPhone 6,6 Plus, 5s, 5, Galaxy S5, S4 S3, Samsung Galaxy Note4,Note 3, Note 2,LG Optimus,LG G3,G2,MOTO X,Most Android Smart Phones and Tablets and other Blu
review_headline: Surprisingly good for a shower speaker
review_body:
There were a few areas of which I was skeptical when I accepted a review sample of this speaker. The first was the rated low end frequency, which is 120Hz. That is six times higher than most speakers, which are in the 20Hz range. The second was my prior experience with shower speakers - not too impressive.

This speaker impressed me. The higher frequency response of the bass does not appreciably hurt the sound quality. Granted, it is not thumping, but it is more than sufficient for the music I prefer (jazz). More importantly, the high end does not break up at maximum volume, nor does it sound tinny. The mid range is excellent - full and rich, and that is part of the reason why this speaker sounds so good with the higher bass frequency response.

Volume is more than sufficient for up close (up to three meters), and for streaming music in the shower it actually performs well. The earlier generation of shower speakers were abysmal in this area. This one shows some attention to design and improvement over the earlier generations from all brands (I have been testing bluetooth speakers for the past two years and have noticed a recent trend among all brands of vast improvements and this one is no exception.

Note that for making and receiving phone calls in a shower this just does not work. The cascade of water masks incoming and outgoing calls to the point where they are unintelligible unless you turn off the shower during the call. I suspect that all speakers that have phone functions will exhibit the same problems in a running shower.

I get an easy three hours of continuous play time from mine. I tested it in a shower, but I use it affixed to my refrigerator so I can enjoy music while cooking.

A few other notes: this one goes into pairing mode as soon as it's turned on, so it's easy to pair, connect and stream music. Because it has a rubber (or silicone) covering it's also rugged and perfect for outdoors activities and harsh environments.nd harsh environments.

product_title: AIMS Power 3000W Pure Sine Wave Inverter 24 Volt PWRIG300024120S
review_body: So far I love my aims inverter. I can run everything in my home that is 120 volts - when my solar panels are getting a sunny day. I had to use the hardwire connection because the breakers in the plug-in receptacles would not hold my load. I bought a 3000 watt inverter from China because it was cheap; but like they say - you get what you pay for. It lasted 3 days. Don't waste your money - this aims inverter is industrial grade. I am hoping to use it for several years. My electric bill is cut in half so far. If it keeps on producing power for me like it has been - I don't know how I could be happier with it. One of the things that I have noticed is - some of the aims inverters are not rated for marine or industrial use. Beware of them - even if the have the aims name on them.

product_title: IG-A03L: i.Trek Vent Mount with 2.5" Long Spring Lock Hooks for Garmin Nuvi GPS
review_headline: After reading the favorable reviews here ...
review_body: After reading many favorable reviews here, I have decided and totally bought four of this iTrek vent mounts in the past two to three years. Here is my experience of the long-term use of these vent mounts.    PROS:  *** Very neat design idea of using the air vent louvers to mount the GPS units - especially as compared with the windshield suction cup or the dashboard beanbag type. iTrek is one of the earlier brand names to offer the GPS vent mount.    CONS:  *** The mount makes the air vent un-adjustable to the desired direction of blowing wind. It blocks the cold air out from the air condition during the summer, and warm heater air in the winter. The mount and the GPS itself could be very hot if the heater is used inside the car during the winter time or if in the hot summer days when the car parking directly under the sun.  *** Very cheap plastic construction - It won't last for two years of cycling hot summers and cold winters. Nearly all the favorable reviews here are written by the users who didn't have the chance to use this mount for long.  *** Be extremely careful about the spring and the plastic clips. Spring may bounce out and the plastic clips may snap off when you try to mount it into the vent. The springs of the 2.5\\" long ones are so easily getting lost and the 2.5\\" plastic clip can become bent because of the hot air.  *** No Lifetime Warranty: Unlike other manufacturers, iTrek hasn't offered the free replacement for the missing or broken parts. For other manufacturers, such as the ARKON vent mounts, you only need to go to their website, fill out the form and get the replacement for the broken or missing parts ( https://www.arkon.com/cgi-bin/sc/order.cgi?storeid=*10ba3248a71724402ff6&dbname=products&sku=SP-GN047-RVC-POM&function=add ). If you have to use a vent GPS mount, use the one comes with the lifetime warranty.  *** Overly priced with respect to the extremely cheap quality of the construction. It is definitely a pitiful marketing decision to save every penny of the manufacture cost to get the maximum profit. You basically pay the high price for the design idea.

product_title: Discount Keyless Green Replacement 4 Button Case and Glow in the Dark Button Pad Compatible with Ford, Lincoln, and Mercury Remotes
review_body:
Review update 2/5/2015
-----------------------
I've had this case on for a month now - and it has held up perfectly. There are no flaws in it whatsoever. My girlfriend uses it primarily, and flings it in and out of her purse daily - It is NOT treated with care.

The buttons light up BRIGHT after they sit under some light. Our key-hook location in the house is right by lights, so these buttons glow STUPID BRIGHT - its hilarious.

I would definitely buy again.

--------------------------

This was a perfect replacement case for my Mercury Mountaineer remote - However I think it will work with any other Ford of similar FOB style.

I opened the old one, took out the battery and the board, and swapped it into the new case. The battery seemed a little loose in the new case, but once you snap it together it is very secure, and doesn't move around at all (I tries shaking it by my ear, no noise).

As an added bonus- the buttons press much easier/nicer! The rubber gel that the buttons are made out of is slightly firmer, and it presses with much more ease.

product_title: Precision Power i640.5 PPI iON Series 540 Watts Class D 5-Channel Amplifier
review_body: I have this hooked up to stock speakers now using stock wiring plus an aftermarket JBL GTO 12\\" subwoofer at 2-ohms.  Source is a Clarion CZ702.  Shortly I'll have Polk dB speakers installed in the car but I figure now is a good time as any to give a quick review of this amp.  The specifications, especially the S/N ratio, aren't spectacular.  Nevertheless, it sounds fine enough and it is indeed tiny.  I don't have any noise or hiss and it reaches clipping with the 5V pre-amp signal from my HU at approximately 1/4\\" plus a teensy bit turn on the gain, which is expected.  Due to space requirements, it has to have RCA dongles vs. direct RCA ports on the amp.  This was kind of annoying to deal with and make look presentable (even though it will reside under a seat) but it actually saved my but because the location I chose wouldn't have allowed for RCAs directly plugged into the amplifier anyway.  Just be prepared to hide and secure six RCA connections somewhere.  It is putting out at least more power than my Clarion HU - the stock speakers are not having fun with this amp.  I have tuned the amp using a SMD DD-1 so no clipped signals, it's just that the stock speakers get maxed out pretty easily - it's a little funny, actually.  The sub channel, for some reason, came with the Bass Boost 100% turned on and the crossover at its lowest Hz setting... I forgot to check this and thought at first the sub channel sucked.  But once I fixed that I was surprised.  It's not the strongest sub channel on earth, let's be honest.  Is it putting out an actual 350 watts?  Pff.. I've heard louder at 350 watts but could just be the JBL sub.  It does get loud, though.  And it's nice it comes with a bass knob - although, like ever other bass knob except JL Audio's, it pretty much is just an on/off switch more or less.  Figure I'll come back and report on how it fairs with aftermarket speakers.

product_title: 32gb Blue Slim 1.8" 4th LCD Mp3 Mp4 Player Fm Radio Video Player with Accessories
review_headline: Should be a kids' meal toy
review_body:
Remember hearing, "You get what you pay for"? Well that is generally the rule here. I messed around with it for 20 minutes to figure out how it works, which is a lot different in regards to navigation and button configuration than the ipod, zune, and sandisk mp3 devices I've owned. For example, instead of pressing the down button to scroll down you press the right button; instead of pressing the middle select button to select you will press the menu button (top button). Those are just a few of the things that make this device nonsensical. When you place folders with mp3 files (MP4s don't seem to work), it plays them in some order I can't figure out and you cannot select which folder plays. And you must number your mp3 files to give them any sort of order. This flaw for the vast majority of music lovers is a complete DEALBREAKER.

Let me sum it up...
Good: Lot of space and battery life
It's small and very lightweight
Bad: Can't select particular artists to listen to or what order they play in.
It's made of the same plastic that toys are from Wendy's kids meals (or at least easily comparable).
Ugly: These should be included in kids meals as they are as cheap as any electronic can get.

Therefore, if you are particular about what you are listening to at any given moment (who isn't? that's odd to me) then this device isn't for you.

product_title: Magicfly Wireless RF Item Locator Key Finder 1 RF Transmitter and 6 Receivers
review_headline: She is very functional still but tends to hide important things like her purse or keys thinking they will get lost
review_body: My elderly mom has Alzheimer's.  She is very functional still but tends to hide important things like her purse or keys thinking they will get lost. Problem is that she then forgets where she put it.  We bought this item locator and has so far worked pretty well.  It's not cheaply made, the locators are small enough that I hid it inside her purse lining.  I put another one in her keychain.  I wish they where flatter to stick it to her cellphone.  The alarm sound is decent, it narrowed down the search to the room and then to the drawer where she hid it ( on purpose, to test it).  Overall, this was a good product for the purpose we had and more importantly the price was reasonable.

product_title: E-PRANCE Newest B48 Super HD 1296P Car Dash Camera
review_headline: Awesome camera, Awesome quality video, great price!!!
review_body:
I absolutely love this camera. Being a former law enforcement officer I have seen MANY accidents where a camera could have helped an innocent person not bet the victim of insurance fraud. The video quality is TOP NOTCH. I ordered the 64gb micro sdxc memory card and it records A LOT of video. U would strongly suggest ordering the lens filter, think it sells for around $10. Down here in Sunny Florida it can distort the camera...the filter makes a HUGE difference. Plus it protects the lens from the bright sun.

Pros:
Love the suction cup mount
Video is top quality
Camera is small and discreet
Power cord for cigarette lighter is VERY LONG
Easy to upload the video to your computer

Cons:

Only shows speed in Kilometers (but can easily by changed using other programs other then the one that came with it)
Microphone seems to be a little weak..and voices tend to be muffled..but still understandable

Regardless of the 2 cons...that's all I can really think of with this camera. Love it....and HIGHLY recommend anyone and everyone to pay the money and order one. Can save you from insurance fraud, mistaken identity by police running radar (as you speed is always shown on video), red light camera errors...etc.....

Feel free to contact me with any questions!!

product_title: Aukey MUSE Portable Wireless Bluetooth Speaker, 10 Hour Playtime, Dual 5W Driver, Enhanced Bass, Full, High-Def. Sound, Built in Mic, 3.5mm AUX Port (SK-M2, Silver)
review_body:
After playing with this unit for couple days I decided to return it. The unit has average sound for its size and I'm get better sound from a smaller coosh speaker. What's really annoying is that every time unit is turned on, paired, or connected via aux there is a voice confirmation in a funny at first accent that gets old very quickly. I just want the unit to play the music not to talk to me especially because there are only two inputs and I know if I'm using aux or bluetooth. Also when volume button is held to turn it up to the max the speaker lets a very strong beep to let you know it can't go any louder. This too is annoying. Buttons can be hit and miss and they function only when you feel them click under your finger.
I liked that the unit has a rubber foot which keeps it from moving around from vibration. It paired quickly and reliably but the range was a problem. My wifi could be interfering with it so I think I'll go with long range unit with stronger bluetooth reception.

Overall a decent unit that looks nice but can be more polished for better experience.

review_headline: It is compact and with the mps built in makes it nice to have your music and your maps
review_body: Being blind I am always trying new technologies. I received my captain a year ago so I have had time to play with it. You'll find it a little tricky at first learning the buttons and voice commands. Its smaller then the Trekker breeze so not as tuff physically to carry or as heavy, yet you give up a little durability. It is Mac compatible where the trekker is not. Its connection software can be a bit finicky too. In time it does get easier as you find all the little tricks and bug. It is compact and with the mps built in makes it nice to have your music and your maps. My thoughts are its a good product a bit pricey for some considering many who are blind are on fixed incomes, I think with technology today being so abundant the cost should be lower, since you can also download a app for you iPhones and droids.

review_headline: Best sound and good for whacking people with....
review_body: Yes thats what the title say. I'll get to the whacking part but first the sound. I bought a Sharkk, ECPower and an EasyACC blue tooth speaker and this one blew the competition right off. Bass is clear and deep. Clarity even at max volume. Lasted 4 hours at max volume. I work for American Airlines Cargo and we can hear the sound from one end of the warehouse to the other end without any forklifts running. Got my device yesterday afternoon charged it and went to bed to work on my graveyard shift. Walk out of my apartment to the street where i parked my car. Got hold up at knife point by 2 ppl demanding my wallet went in to my bag to grab my wallet when i touch the speaker. Instead of the wallet i took the speaker out and whack the guy on the side of his head. the other one try to bum rush me but instead i spearhead the blunt end of the speaker into his face. He falls back and started to run away. Called 911 and told the cops what happened. The guy i hit on the side of the head was still unconscious. The speaker didnt even have a dent or any minor damage except for some blood stains. Cops picked the second guy that ran away and they have me id him. Wow did not almost recognized his face. The speaker broke his nose and was bleeding all over. This is one tough speaker to actually withstand a full force of bitch slap on a guys head and blunting someone straight into their face. Very well made if theres a 10 star ill give this thing a 100 instead. Now im gonna order one more just in case another incident happen i might end up breaking it.

product_title: Apple Ipod Nano 7th Generation, 16GB, Silver
review_headline: The device itself is pretty amazing, but the software and the quality of ...
review_body: I've had an iPod for a long time (about 8+ years). The device itself is pretty amazing, but the software and the quality of Apple support easily makes this a 1 star item. It should be noted that once your iPod is set up, if you connect it to any other computer and attempt to run iTunes it will erase all of the music on your iPod. Also, if you don't buy your music on iTunes, which I don't as it's much cheaper on other websites, it can make managing the music in iTunes a nightmare. As far as the Apple support, I have been lied to, hung up on, and have ended up talking to people who are very rude almost 100% of the time. And they charge $30 to talk to a technician with no guarantee of actually being able to help you. When the iPod works, it works well but when it doesn't the chances of you being able to resolve the issue without paying a substantial fee is almost nonexistent. Also, the amount of time I have spent over the years tying to get iTunes to work and constantly trying to figure out the new iTunes software (which is released very frequently) adds up to an impressive amount of hours. I would not recommend this to any of my friends or family.

product_title: HIGH QUALITY 6ft 5PK Multi-Color Flat Noodle Lightning to USB Cable for iPhone 5 / 5C / 5S / 6 / 6 Plus (Latest IOS Supported) iPad Mini iPod Touch 5th Air Gen - 8 pin to USB (blk/red/wht/blu/grn)
review_headline: Took a chance - glad I did.
review_body:
For the price (under $4/cable), you cannot really complain.
The cables all worked out of the package and are made well. They do not feel or look cheap (as I expected they would).
The length is great too.

Charged iphone 5, 6, ipad mini and ipad mini 2 correctly on day 1 and 2.
Charge speed seemed slower than standard lightning cable, but worked nonetheless.

Then on day 3, the "incompatible device" message came up on iphone 6. (blue cable). but it charges the ipad mini no problem.
Plugged same cable back into the iphone 6 and no message.

The cables all work, but I question the longevity of them,
However, for this price for FIVE lightning cables (I paid $3/ea), I cannot complain if even only 1 cable works of the bunch.

I would recommend them if you are looking for some colored cables with a nice length, or to even have as a backup in your car or office.

product_title: Aweek® Replacement Battery Ni-MH 7.2V 1400mAh NNTN4851AC Battery for Motorola GP3688 GP3188 CP040 CP150 CP200 PR400 Two Way Radios
review_headline: Do not buy for use with CP200!
review_body: We did not buy these batteries direct from this seller, they came as new with our CP200 purchase on Amazon. Although the batteries appear to be new, they are not the original Standard CP200 Batteries (Li-ion, 2250 mAh, 7.5V - NNTN4497_R). They are cheap after market batteries. The specs on these batteries are as follows: (Ni-MH, 1400mAh, 7.2V - NNTN4851AC). These batteries are absolute garbage. They do not hold a charge. Most of them a completely dead despite showing they are charged on the charger. Some of them will work in the radio for about an hour of standby time before going dead. Compared to original batteries that have 12+ hours of standby time with no issue. I do not recommend these batteries with CP200s as they simply do not work. I am not sure about their performance on other radios.

product_title: Tomameri Portable MP4 Player MP3 Player Video Player with Photo Viewer , E-Book Reader , Voice Recorder + 8 GB Micro SD Card (Black)
review_headline: The only reason to buy this is to see how well Amazon's return policy works
review_body: Worthless Junk. My Ipod broke, and after having it for several years, I realized, the only thing I really ever used it for was playlists of a hundred songs, so why buy another ipod. I shopped around Amazon, and this seemed to be the best option. I knew it wasn't going to be my ipod, or even a zune, but I figured it would be okay for the next couple of years while I finish grad school and don't have a ton of money.    Nope. Absolute trash. Zero instructions to operate. Fortunately, I'm not terrible at electronics, so I figured it all out, but its not exactly an intuitive system. There's one menu with the EQ, shuffle and repeat options that you can only access while music is playing. Then there's a separate menu for when music is paused. Volume is a bit clunky, but again, all of this would have been forgivable for the price.    Then I actually tried to use it. Every 5-15 minutes, it stops, and freezes. The only way to unfreeze it is to do a total shut off and on with the top button. I thought, maybe I'm just a very vigorous walker, and it will be okay when the thing is just sitting on a table not moving. Nope. Its just a piece of s*** technology.    Don't waste your money on it unless you want to be disappointed.

review_body: This is a true bargain. But you should be aware of its capabilities. It only will play MP3 files, not the other common formats. It loses its place every time you turn it off. You can plug it into your computer to charge it, but your computer will not be able to access the data. To change data you must remove chip and put it into an adapter and plug into computer. Also remember that when you buy one of these you need to also buy a data chip, headphones and a charging wire. You will see that this and other vendors sell it with or without needed components. That said, mine seems durable, light and functional. I have purchased several brands to experiment with because I plan to give them to employees with training audio on them. I paid more for others of less quality. I suspect that exercise time is a strong point for this unit. At the beach I can go running and get rained on before getting home. I would much rather that happened to a $5 item than my smart phone.

product_title: PowerBoost X1 2600mAh Premium Portable iPhone Charger Rechargeable Battery With USB To 8-pin Connector Cable (Works with iPhones 5 / 5s / 6) And With USB To Micro USB Cable (Works With Most Android Phones) from Duroplus
review_body:
Expecting this PowerBoost Charge, I left home with a barely charged phone. About an hour later it was completely dead. I plugged it into boost and it quickly recharged enough to send and receive phone calls on my IPHONE 6 Plus. It did not charge it all the way in the 30 minutes I was gone. It is simply a way to boost your power until you can get home and do a full charge. The product did warm up and cause the phone to warm as well, but it did not get too hot to handle. However I was able to charge my 5c in about 2 hours with no warming of either product.
I was sent the product to review and only given the blue option. Which for a women with a dark hole in her purse worked well, it was easily spotted.
The thing I am going to have to remember is how many times I use the product. I can see using it 500 times within a year and forgetting what number I am on. A counter of some type so you can order your replacement and not be wondering if you had reached the 500 count.
It is wonderful item, and will be a great addition to my purse. No more excuses my phone was dead.

product_title: USPRO® USB Programming Cable for BaoFeng UV-5R/5RA/5R Plus/5RE/UV3R plus/BF-888S
review_headline: Cable works perfectly with Baofaeng UV-5RA
review_body: This cable worked perfectly with my Baofaeng UV-5RA; I never even looked at the included CD.  My Win 7 netbook downloaded the proper driver automatically, and Windows device manager confirmed under PORTS, proper installation of PROLIFIC USB-to-SERIAL COMM PORT (COM 5).  I used CHIRP programming software.  After you use your computer, CHIRP, and this cable to upload your entries to the UV-5RA, do the following to see alpha-tags on the UV-5RA rather than frequencies.  Go into the Baofeng UV-5RA menu to \\"MDF-A\\" for the A band and use arrow keys to select \\"NAME\\", then press MENU key to save.  Then go into UV-5RA menu to \\"MDF-B\\", use arrow keys to select \\"NAME\\", then press MENU key to save.  Your CHIRP uploaded selections will now be seen on the UV-5RA display screen with alpha-tags rather than frequencies (if that is your wont).  (K6VCI)

product_title: Pioneer DEH-X8700BH - CD Receiver with Full Dot LCD Display, Bluetooth, HD Radio, Siri Eyes Free, USB Playback, Android Music Support, and Pandora
review_body:
My only major gripe is the way the presets are stored, it's a bit complicated and involved requiring going into the menu a few levels. Also, my car is older and lacks steering wheel controls, so changing to the next track when the CD player or Bluetooth is selected requires the use of the toggle switch behind the large volume button. It's terrible, difficult to use, awkward to hold and seems to me like a complete afterthought.

Thankfully this unit does include a dedicated dimmer input, I believe this is the lowest priced unit in their line up that includes this feature, which I find ridiculous. I can understand perhaps the lowest offering lacking that input, but for anything > $100, unnacceptable.

Other than that, Bluetooth is flawless, the unit looks good and is just a few design flaws in my opinion from being perfect.

The lack of buttons - presets in particular, while attractive definitely hurts the day to day usability of this head unit for my particular application.

product_title: Ebaco ® HDMI 1x2 Powered 3D Amplifier Splitter for Dual Display with Full HD 1080P, 3D, HDCP, Deep Color, HD Audio Support
review_headline: Worst experience I have ever had with any piece of electronic equipment
review_body:
Usually I can always find the good in a product. I rarely have complaints and I always take the time to troubleshoot before ever releasing a review of a product. Having said that, this product is absolutely awful. After connecting the device and going through every troubleshooting process imaginable I have come to the conclusion that this device does not come close to living up to it's claim. I will say that it splits the HDMI signal. It splits it straight in half to a 480p resolution to each screen. I assumed it was an issue in being non compliant with the Playstation 4 so I connected it with every HDMI device in my home including a Playstation 3 (which is blatantly advertised as being compliant on the products box) and had the exact same result. Two DVD Players, one blu-ray player, a Plastation3 and a Playstation 4; all with the result of splitting the resolution directly in half.

This product in no way lives up to it's claims and I would not recommend that anyone purchase this splitter. If in all of my technical knowledge, I cannot make this device operate as advertised then I assure you it is not possible. If you are looking for a quality HD splitter for any purpose I strongly recommend looking elsewhere. I've heard good things about Orei and a more expensive rocketfish model but have no experience but I would look there instead. Also the product description is highly deceiving upon further review. The box says that the product is full 4k capable as well but the Amazon listing says that it will only support resolutions up to 1920x1200 which is a far cry from 4k resolution.

Now for the Pros and Cons.

Pros:
-- Absolutely none

Cons:
-- Cheap construction that is sure to be highly susceptible to electrostatic shock
-- Does not live up to the billing of being able to duplicate a 1080p resolution
-- Cuts your resolution in half
-- False advertising on the box
-- Did not even reproduce audio

Would I recommend this product to anyone? Absolutely not.

product_title: DBPOWER Mini Waterproof GPS Tracker Locator with Google Map Great for Kids, Pets, Cars or Vehicles Etc
review_headline: No Text Responses and Faulty Charger
review_body:
Received as described, well boxed and with all accessories. Instructions were minimal but understandable. I used a known working SIM card and got a good GPS signal quickly. I called the device and promptly received a link to Google maps with an accurate location. I then set the time and received a text response.

That was the last text response I received for any command I tried - password, admin, RST, format, G, sos, nothing worked. I called the device again and got the appropriate text. I removed the SIM card and put it into a phone and successfully texted back and forth numerous times. I placed it back into the device, no texts.

I spent about three hours trying to get it to work. In addition to the above, the charging dock does not make a good connection. The LED flickers off and on unless the dock is positioned just right. As this item is currently out-of-stock, I'm returning for a refund.

product_title: AutoBar Support Grab Handle - A Handy 3-In-1 Car Access And Safety Tool – Exit and Entry Assist Mobility Aid Bar, Emergency Escape Seatbelt Cutter, Rescue Glass Window Breaker Hammer – Saves Time And Effort for People Suffering From Physical Infirmity; Bad Back, Lumbar Pain, Hip And Knee Injuries, Or Arthritis Problems.
review_headline: It works just remember if you cut the seat belt to make sure it works it will cost you over $100 to replace it - my son/genius
review_body:
Well I know that this item works great to cut a seat belt if it is stuck and you can't get out the normal way but beware - replacing a seat belt is over $100 and I know - I showed this to my family and I am impressed with the size and weight of this bar - it is heavy - it could be a weapon used to bludgeon someone attacking you - or break a window to escape your car in an emergency -

Also it can be used as a handle to help you get in and out of your car - I have an older friend who needs this to get in and out of the car without grabbing onto a person and almost knocking them over - this is a great tool to have in your car - punch out the window - cut the seat belt - get out safely -

The seat belt cutter works - my son tried it because he was curious - so next time I will not be so excited about showing my kids what a cutter like this can cut - a $100 mistake and a $100 lesson learned - when kids are old enough to drive is the time to tell them and then tell them how much it will cost it they are curious to see if it really does work.

I received this item for an honest review.

product_title: iXCC Multi pack Lightning cable
review_headline: including several iPhone 5s and 6s and both mini and standard iPads of pretty much every generation since the iPad was first rel
review_body:
I don't review products or books very often at all, despite buying frequently from Amazon and being a Prime member for many years. When I write it's because I am uniquely impressed or distressed by a product, or because I had had to spend a lot of time seeking a solution to a particular problem and hope that I can save others some of that effort.

This situation fits both categories. I own many Apple devices, including several iPhone 5s and 6s and both mini and standard iPads of pretty much every generation since the iPad was first released. They are used by family members and colleagues in my business setting. Finding cables that cost less than Apple's, while providing quality matching theirs, and not running afoul of the idiotic error messages that most of my devices seem, suddenly, out of nowhere, to start issuing when using non-certified (or allegedly-certified) products has become both a crusade and financially essentials.

The only cables I have come across -- and I have tried everything from those that come shipped directly from China and cost almost nothing to the Monoprice cables that are widely reviewed as being rock solid -- that have consistently worked, and worked without any whisper of question ... just seamlessly worked with all devices over an extended period of time ... are these. And iXCC's tech support and warranty policies have been excellent (one cable had a problem with its lightning connector and was swiftly replaced).

At present, they are the only lightning cables I am buying.

product_title: Tomameri Portable MP4 Player MP3 Player Video Player with Photo Viewer , E-Book Reader , Voice Recorder + 8 GB Micro SD Card (Blue)
review_body:
I read the other reviews, noting that when people had a problem with this product, it was pretty much always the same problem: the battery would never charge after the first couple days. I thought, perhaps since these was a minority, that I might not have that problem. I was wrong (my mistake).

The fact is, this is a poorly designed player. The casing is weak plastic that I suspect would shatter upon its first drop (and we all do drop them on occasion, right?). The controls did not make sense, as you had to hit the up (menu) button to select something but the middle button (which on most models is the select key) was the back-up button. The side-scroll buttons only made things go up and down and the folders were a ridiculous mess. The screen resolution was terrible. I didn't expect much, but my Gameboy Micro from 10 years ago has better screen resolution. Technology has improved, friends, so it shouldn't be this bad even on such a cheap unit.

And finally, the battery is a mess. It arrived "fully charged" but drained of 70% of its power just in the 1/2 hour I used it to learn the ridiculous controls. Then, after listening to 30 minutes of music and watching 1 22-minute tv show, it died and never took a charge again. I used multiple outlets (both USB and wall plugs), multiple cables (I had some old cables that were compatible), but nothing worked. It said it was charging, but never accepted the charge. So it remained dead.

I bought this just to have something for my kids to listen to in the car, but it couldn't even do that. So I gave up and returned it. I highly recommend that you avoid this product. I suspect that most of the positive reviews were from people who liked it on day one (I didn't hate it on day 1) but by day 3 it was dead and they never bothered to update their review.

product_title: Kingtop Portable Bluetooth Speakers with Unique Wooden Appearance Powerful Sound Speakers for Iphone Ipad Android
review_headline: Decent Bluetooth Speaker – Not Real Wood Though
review_body:
Bluetooth speakers on Amazon are a dime a dozen, but this one from SoulBuddy takes a different approach to the design. This speaker weighs in at a little over 6 oz. and is made of plastic. On first glance you would think it is made of wood, but it is not. It has a “bamboo effect”. This is a fancy way of saying that is looks like wood. Near the bottom of the speaker there is a transparent ring that lights up blue and let you know that it is on. A rubber ring on the bottom of the speaker helps keep it from moving when you access the buttons on the back.

Pairing is quick and easy. Go to the Bluetooth setting in your device, select MYHAKU-6 and you’re all set. It comes with a USB charging cable. There is also a AUX port if you choose not to use Bluetooth steaming. The top of the speaker angles slightly to better project the sound. The power switch is located on the underside of the unit. There are four small buttons situated on the back of the speaker – play/pause, forward, backward and phone. The phone button allows you to answers calls via your phone by pressing the button. Sound quality both ways while talking on the phone was adequate.

The sound quality is OK for a speaker at this price point. The bass is not strong and sounded a bit tinny at times. There also was a low hiss that was audible when music was not playing. With a 1,000 mAh battery, it will last you hours.

This is a decent speaker for about $25 that looks better than it sounds.

Product sample.

product_title: E-PRANCE® Mini 0805 Car Dashboard Camera Video Recorder, 2304*1296P Super HD, 1920*1080P Full HD, 135 Degree Wide Angle Lens, G-sensor, WDR, HDR, H.264, Motion Detection Hidden Car DVR Black Box
review_body:
Initially I had a lot of question/problems with this dash cam. E-Prance responded promptly with every e-mail I sent. If my problems had not been resolved I could have sent the unit back with postage paid for. My experiences were not smooth sailing like the u-tube video on this item. It turns out several of my SD cards I used were not compatable and the battery did not have a charge. After several series of e-mail correspondence the problems were solved and now after about one month of usage the 0805 dash cam seems to be working fine. I do like the unit and would recommend it's purchase to anyone looking for a dash cam. The only reason I gave it 4 stars is the down loading of its videos to the computer. I have another dash cam that when down loading it files, it creates separate files every time the power is turned on and off which is many times in the course of short trips. This is a plus to a person like me that is very technically challenged. The 0805 when down loading its files to the computer displays them, not in folder form, but all together in one continuous line of videos. I find this hard to navigate when searching for a particular 1, 3, or
5 minuet video. Looking for a reasonably priced cam that has a good quality picture, this is it. I did however change the sticky tape on the mounting bracket so as to make it a little more non obvious.

review_body: Took a chance and bought this as a cheap alternative sound system for a RzR 570 and was very pleased with the outcome. Was able to ride all day long in rough terrain and varying speeds with no issues. Since this was a two part system, Main head unit and a remote mount controller, I was able to mount the main unit deep under the dash where its not seen or in the way and mount the remote controller in the overhead console. Only had 2 speakers hooked up but was plenty loud, while riding only had to raise the volume to 75%, later I plan to hook up two more speakers. All in all a great system at a great price, not hesitant to recommend to fellow riders on a budget.

product_title: Kingtop Portable Bluetooth Speakers with Unique Wooden Appearance Powerful Sound Speakers for Iphone Ipad Android
review_headline: Suffers from Piercing Treble when at Max Volume - Not Best for Beat Driven Crunk
review_body:
[[VIDEOID:b5612d76bbeb741cd012935ade746f79]]Great looking speaker, but it suffers when at MAX volume. Suffers badly. As shown in my video, the best listening range is going to be about 2/3rds up on your device - beyond that, and an uncomfortable piercing quality due to extreme treble enters in. However, a virtual EQ does help quite a bit in that respect. Still weak in the bass, though, so not your best choice for crunking, unless you are into the old school crunk, real old school, like Bach and other baroque music. (Heh).

So as long as your music preference isn't bass driven, and you either don't MAX the volume or get yourself a virtual EQ (the premium one I use is available here on the Amazon Appstore, Music Volume EQ ), you will be pleased with this.

-- I received this as a complimentary review product with the aim of hopefully elucidating features and drawbacks that may help you ultimately decide what fits your needs and budget best.

How did this pass inspection? Altec sold out their name to let this fly. They should be ashamed their name is used to peddle this utterly defective product. If I'd been paying closer attention it would have gone back but by the time I realized it would never work properly it was too late to return it. ALTEC is no longer a quality name. product_title: GMYLE Bluetooth Audio Receiver NFC-Enabled Music for Home Stereo
review_body:
Works flawlessly for us. The BT receiver was completely plug and play with no issues whatsoever. Unlike some other vendors, this unit ~includes~ the 1/8" to stereo RCA cable that I would have had to otherwise buy to use with my home audio receiver, as well as including the USB charging cable and AC adapter. The unit is small enough to be taken on the road and used in the car as well. Audio quality is crystal clear and fidelity sounds very good. I didn't have any perceptible lag when I started/stopped an audio stream from a cellphone, although I didn't test extensively. I'll update the review once I try the NFC more extensively - I tried it once in passing and it didn't work, but it may have been operator error on my part.

I'm deducting one star because I, too, think the unit should be able to sync to multiple devices. Updating the BT chip to a newer BT 3 or 4 unit would be nice as well, but not critical in this price range, especially with all it does and includes.

product_title: TERMN-8R Dual Band (6 Band RX) (VHF/UHF) GMRS, MURS, Amateur (Ham), Commercial Portable Two-Way Radio
review_headline: Has Potential for Emergency Comm Purposes but Antenna is Weak Point
review_body: Most of the other reviews seem to be coming from hams who are experienced with more expensive HTs and the cheaper ones.  I don't have any experience with the more expensive Icom or Kenwood HTs.  My first HT was a Baofeng.  With that said, I am viewing this as a potential upgrade from the $30-$50 Baofeng. I am involved with Community Emergency Response Team (CERT) and we are using FRS/GMRS for local communications, and ham frequencies for longer range communications.  There's an interest in using MURS for local communications as well but the CERT program requires that we do everything legally and since there aren't many MURS certified radios out there (and until now, none available for purchase from Amazon) this represents a problem.  With that said, this radio presents an opportunity:  FCC Part 90, Part 95, and Part 97 certified for use on commercial, GMRS, MURS, and ham frequencies and under $150.  The question is, does it work well enough and easy enough to recommend to people who are picking up $60 FRS/GMRS radio bubble packs? To be clear, this radio cannot do FRS legally due to the antenna being replaceable (power level is also restricted on FRS only frequencies to .5 watt but this could theoretically be restricted via software) but can access the shared FRS/GMRS channels and the dedicated GMRS channels.  So you have Motorola FRS radio channels 1-7 and then 15-22 when comparing radios.  Channels 8-14 are FRS only.  In order to legally use the GMRS frequencies you need to have a GMRS FCC license ($90 for 5 years and is good for your entire immediate family) but MURS is license free. One other note is that this radio does have the GMRS repeater channels built in which are only available on the higher end bubble pack radios. To switch from ham to GMRS or to MURS, you need to power off the radio, hold down a key, turn it on, then switch to the PART 95 option and then to Normal, GMRS, or MURS.  This also restricts you to monitoring one channel. Build quality seems good.  The radio feels substantial in your hand but seems fat compared to a Baofeng UV-82.  I do like the charging port built into the battery that will allow you to use a car charger.  The Baofengs are limited to a battery eliminator in the car. From a programming stand point, right now you're limited to hand programming or using the AnyTone provided free software (from the anytonetech.com website).  Chirp will hopefully have this model added soon.  Unfortunately with that said, the AnyTone software is limited in that you cannot copy and paste. Further, there is no "offset" field and you actually need to type in the receive and transmit frequencies manually in the software. As for manual operation, quite frankly I prefer the Baofeng menu system.  There you hit the menu button and navigate up and down through the menu to find what you want, hit menu, change the setting, hit menu again to accept.  With the AnyTone, you need to hit func, 8, use the channel selector knob to navigate then either hit 1 to edit the menu or use the main or v/m buttons to edit depending on your mode.  I still haven't figured out how to set the direction of the repeater offset.  Also on 2m, the offset defaulted to 5.0Mhz (standard for 70cm but not for 2m) and I didn't seem to have an option to type in the offset I wanted so I had to use the channel selector knob to dial it all the way down to 0.6Mhz. The bank system is a good idea but switching into bank mode requires diving into the menu system and is more likely to have you assigning a channel to a bank than switching you into bank mode. Learning curve aside, the manual is quite decent and well written (5/5 stars) if you like to read manuals.  I just prefer a device to be intuitive so that I only need to use the manual to do advanced features.  3/5 stars here. The biggest problem I have is the stock antenna. It appears to be cut for ham frequencies and barely covers GMRS or MURS.  This represents a problem because side-by-side a bubble pack FRS $30 radio will out perform this radio on GMRS.  In testing, I could not hear our base camp on the TERMN-8R but I could hear them on a Motorola FRS/GMRS radio.  On the other hand, they were able to hear me when I transmitted from the AnyTone.  The same occurred when testing MURS.  With the default squelch of 3 set, I was unable to hear transmissions and they reported that my transmissions were weak and barely breaking squelch.  Using the Baofeng UV-82 antenna seems to improve a little bit but still not enough to make this radio one I can recommend for CERT communications. I am currently looking into finding a better, wider band antenna to pair with this radio and will update the review if I find one.  Update:  I did a side-by-side comparison using a Kenwood TM-V71a mobile ham radio attached to a Comet CA-2x4SR Search and Rescue antenna, the Anytone TERMN-8R, and the Baofeng UV-82.  I was monitoring a radio check in over FRS/GMRS 2. Most of the people transmitting were using bubble pack FRS radios.  The Kenwood heard everything without any issue.  The Baofeng heard 95% of the traffic and the only issue I noticed was that it was a little slow on the receive sometimes - this might be a power save setting.  The Anytone did not pick up a good chunk of the transmissions.  The more distant parties were not picked up.  The transmissions that were picked up on the TERMN-8R were noticeably noisier than both of the other radios.  I did swap the stock antennas between the Baofeng and the Anytone early on and then swapped them back.  It did not seem to make a difference.  I will RMA the Anytone and order another in case I happen to have one that is somehow defective. If I have it in hand next Monday, I'll consider attaching the Anytone to my Comet antenna to see if that improves receive.

review_headline: I read other reviews on what was the best dash-cam to purchase for the money and this was ...
review_body:
The product was what I expected. I read other reviews on what was the best dash-cam to purchase for the money and this was the most recommended for the money of $99.99 US Dollars. The Annabelle chip it has is a newer chip that is mostly only available in more expensive camera's. The instructions for setup and use are a little basic and not specific, but I played around with it a bit and was able to figure it out. I recommend that you connect the USB cable to power up the internal battery and complete your settings with it in hand and setup your date/time stamp and other features before connecting and setting up in the car.
I tested it in the car in the day and tested it in the night. The quality of video is pretty good both day and night.
You need to download the Quick-time program to view the videos and it then loads a specific vehicle program to select what video you want to watch and load it and watch it. You can then take snapshot photos of any part of the video or upload specific video clips.
If you mount the camera in the middle of your car under the mirror area it is hardly noticeable and the angle of the camera will encompass your entire front end of vehicle from left to right with a little bit more on each side (hence the claim of 135 degree angle view).
In short - I would simply say this is a great product for the price.
However, I can't say anything more about how long it lasts or quality over time as I have only had this product for about 5 days.
ID

product_title: Kingtop Portable Bluetooth Speakers with Unique Wooden Appearance Powerful Sound Speakers for Iphone Ipad Android
review_headline: Nice Looking Speaker Doesn't Deliver With Music Listening
review_body:
There are good and bad points to this speaker.

GOOD:

The speaker looks nice and is perfect for sitting on a wooden desk
The device pairs up to Bluetooth devices easily
Sound quality is perfect for talk

BAD:

Not great for music, lack of bass and distortion at high volumes

I really do like the way this speaker looks, it is a shame that the audio quality overall isn't great. I'm a self-professed audio snob and I don't think I'd be happy listening to any types of music on this device due to the lack of bass. I tested it out watching a few baseball games and listening to talk radio and the speaker works great for that purpose.

The bottom line is it all depends what you want to use this speaker for, if it's music you might not be happy but if you're looking for a way to listen to podcasts or other talk-based programming you might love it.

Sample provided for review.

product_title: Generic WY-A1 Universal GPS Speedometer with Over Speed Warning
review_headline: So far it is a great unit. I cut the film into four and ...
review_body: I returned the other similiar GPS HUD (SEI)which took forever to lock on the satellite and when it rained, it never locked on. Plus the other one had button sequence that was complicated and did not have an on/off switch. This one locks on within 10 seconds, Changing from MPH to KPH is one button push. I never thought I would need an on/off button but I found I use it a lot. This is located on the dash and gets very hot in the sun, I don't want it running if it is parked. Also, I shut it off at night so as not to attract attention when parked. So far it is a great unit. I cut the film into four and only used a quarter of it. It auto dims at night and it is bright enough during sunny days. The display is large enough to read easily. The power connector is on the left against the driver door so that the wire can be routed easier. The SEI was on the wrong side making the wire more awkward. Both this unit and SEI came poorly packaged in the box, they rattled and could be damaged with rough courier handling. Don't bother with the SEI.

product_title: Generic GPS Module Aircraft Flight Controller For Arduino
review_headline: Check your Baudrate if you don't get any signal!
review_body:
For everyone having problems with this device: Make sure you set the GPS device BAUDRATE to 9600 in your code!

TinyGPS and ++ libaries by Mikal Hart have the baudrate set to 4800 by default, so it will not work out of the box with this device.

product_title: DC/DC 3.5-30V to 4.0-30V Booster Converter Step Up Voltage Regulator LM2587
review_headline: Easy to use, and does it exactly what it's supposed to.
review_body:
I'm using this to drive LEDs off a couple of AA batteries, and so far it's working great. The low input voltage of 3.5v means even a small power supply like AAs, or some CR2032 lithium-ion batteries can drive enough LEDs to light up a small room. This is very convenient for putting lights in hard to reach places like under a workbench, or inside of a car.

The device has a solid build quality, and even the printing on the pcb is very high quality and clear. The terminals are clearly labeled which makes it very easy to setup even if it's your first time using one of these. The knob to adjust the output voltage is sensitive enough that you can fine tune it to millivolt precision very easily.

I will very likely be buying more of these in the future.

product_title: 8milelake Capri Tools 01025a Disc Brake Caliper Wind Back Tool Kit, 12-piece
review_headline: Inexpensive enough to buy your own set
review_body: The price is inexpensive enough that you can have your own set and order pads online rather than in an auto parts store and borrowing their tool set.  I don't have them side by side, but they seem very similar to a set from Autozone .  In the past with some cars, I have been able to turn the piston back in without the simultaneous down force provided by this tool.  I had to learn the hard way on a Mazda 6 why this tool is needed on some rear brake pistons. I did not give it five stars because of recent use on a 2002 Jetta.  The piston was quite far out (i.e., very worn pads) and the tool in its fully retracted position would not fit into position within the calipers.  It seems reasonable that the tool could have been designed with a bit more clearance, another 8th of an inch.  Pads are sometimes worn worse than what I had.  Also, the sliding turning handle is a bit flimsy and bent a little when extra leverage was used.  The piston in this instance was very resistant, but not the first time in my life I have seen this.  I recommend turning the piston by gripping it on the outside edge with channel locks to loosen it up.  This was how I was able to get the tool into position in the first place, and loose enough to turn in with this tool.

product_title: MSI GTX 750 TI 2GB DDR5 OC 128Bit DVI-D/D-SUB/HDMI N750TI TF 2GD5/OC
review_headline: Has the switch but still would not boot after installation
review_body:
Most would call me too optimistic. Before reviewing this card here's a few questions I tried to find definite answers for questions I had but didn't have much luck.
The Hybrid Bios Switch - There's quite a few contradicting reviews on this very important part. I'll say, it wasn't blatantly obvious but the switch is there. The way I found it was noticing in the insert that UEFI had the number 1 on its side of the switch and Legacy had the number 2. That gave me a 1 and 2 near each other to look for. It sits along the edge of the card back. So its there. If you don't see it you're not looking hard enough or you didn't get the same card I got. Once I saw it I felt like a dummy for missing it.

My computer is an h8-1214. This isn't my normal everyday computer. I either wanted it to become a good gaming computer with this card or our 10 year old son was going to get it for his first computer. The specs on this PC are not bad. Its just an HP model that likes to do everything except gaming.

I had tried upgrading the GPU to another makers version of this card but ended up stuck on the HP splash screen. I then found out about the different bios and how I missed out on having UEFI on this PC by 6 months.

So I popped the case open and flipped the switch to Legacy. Pulled the old Radeon card out and inserted this MSI card. I immediately ran into two problems.

One, the card requires more space than the PCI on my computer has so I opened the empty one above it.

Two, this card is several inches longer than the old Radeon, its also wider and taller. I work in construction engineering so I just readjusted wires, wiggled it until it was in a very tight space. I closed the case, booted it up and there's the HP splash screen again. Stuck. I called a friend who is our tech guy at work. He came by, checked all connections and said it looked like a good install. Still didn't boot. He called HP despite the computer being out of warranty and was told there are multiple issues with upgrading this specific PCs graphic card.

At this point, I decided to ship it back to Amazon and let our son have the PC. The card itself looks really great. The dual fans, color scheme and I'm giving it 4 stars since it does have the switch and I've seen the 750ti in action. Its worth a try for those out there with a non-UEFI computer but I guess I'll just go ahead and try to build my own from scratch.ranty and was told there are multiple issues with upgrading this specific PCs graphic card.

product_title: ASC Ford Mustang Coupe 2005-2014 Dual 12" Subwoofer Custom Fit Sub Box Speaker Enclosure
review_body:
So, let me start off by saying I had to buy this twice, because I got my shipping addresses messed up and I wasn't able to get the company to work with me on shipping after it had already shipped. So just as a note, ensure your shipping address is good before you process! For the overall product, it wasn't what I though I was getting. I purchased Rockford Fosgate P3-2X12 12" 2400W Subwoofers that came with a box. The only problem was that box wouldn't fit in my 2014 Mustang, it was just a little too big. I ended up ordering this box to supplement. When I received it, it was not near the quality of the Rockford Fosgate box I pulled my P3 subs out of. The felt was of lesser quality and some of it was hanging off, dangly and not really glued on too well. Since I had previously called the company to not have to buy it twice, I didn't feel like dealing with them a second time to talk about quality work. So I accepted the shoddy work and went to work. Everything transferred over fine and was going well. When I got to the connectors (there are two connectors, one on each side) I noticed that I could easily pull them off, meaning they were not air tight. That was rather disappointing, because there was nothing there to stop air from escaping and would reduce the overall capability of my subs. They were screwed on, however there is normally a sealant between the wood and the connectors that prevents air from escaping. The other thing to know, is if you have purchased this to complete, it is set up as if the subs were separate, no way to connect your speakers because there are no holes or gaps in the center piece of wood for you to run wire. (This becomes a problem based on how you wire your speakers, pretty much you will need two amps/whatever else you want since you have to treat each as a single 12" sub). I modified my box so that it would work. The box did fit into my trunk though, so that was really the only satisfying thing that had happened. I ended up stripping parts off my Rockford Fosgate box and putting it on this box.

Pros:
1) My 12' P3 subs fit into the holes they were supposed too fit in.
2) The box fit into my trunk as it said it would (2014 Mustang)

Cons:
1) Felt was of lesser quality and was not attached to the box very well
2) Speaker wiring connectors were not air tight
3) Middle compartment in box would not allow for multiple wiring configurations for dual subs without modifications
4) Had to order twice (This is my fault, but was not satisfied with who I talked to about how we can fix it)

Overall, I still wonder how my speakers would kick if they were in a better box. The workmanship was shoddy and I would not recommend this to another customer. I know that many people are probably restricted to custom boxes for smaller trunks. My recommendation for that is just order it online from a custom sub box design site. They will run you about how much buying this twice ran me and will probably be a lot better quality.

product_title: Bluetooth receiver
review_headline: Doosl Audio Receiver Adapter - Bluetooth hands-free music - Easy to use - Plugs in to 3.5mm Aux port - Good sound - Sleek design
review_body:
This is an easy-to-use, very stylish looking, affordable Bluetooth-based receiver from Doosl that allows you to play your music over your car stereo system (or any entertainment system) as long your unit has an 3.5mm Aux port. It essentially turns your car's system into a big Bluetooth jukebox, and it works well. We like this receiver and would recommend it to others.

We used this on our 1998 Jeep: The sound system in that Jeep is not OEM -- it is a later model Sony that does have an Aux port, so we just plugged this device into that port, synced it with my HTC Driod DNA and hit the road listening to Pandora and an MP3 playlist on that phone. It also synced to my son's Samsung Galaxy S3 via NFC, and it sounded loud & clear, but I was not in the mood tonight to listen to his teenage headache inducing \\"music\\" so we mainly stayed my my Droid's Bluetooth transmission.

Once fully charged, which took several hours to complete, the receiver worked well. I was easy to sync with our phones and it played very nicely over the Jeep's stereo system. Its Aux cable is about 20 inches long which was long enough for me to lay the receiver in the tray on top of the dashboard, or down in the cup holder in the front of the center console. The cable is visible but not much of a distraction, and the receiver produced clear sound for us. It worked well and we all liked it.

This device truly is sleek; it weighs in at about one ounce and is just 2.5 inches long, 1.5 inches from side-to-side, and only 3/8th of an inch thick. It works well and takes up almost no space whatsoever. Well done.

The receiver's retail documentation notes that it is covered by an 18 month manufacturers warranty, so if an issue arises within that timeframe I will return here to update the review and let you know what the issue was and how resolution was handled. I did receive this Bluetooth receiver gratis from the seller and put it to use in our Jeep to objectively find out how well it performed. My statements here reflect that testing.

This Doosl Audio Receiver Adapter worked well for us. If you have a car or entertainment system with a 3.5mm Aux port and are looking for a Bluetooth streaming music option of this size, neat style,and affordable price, for use similar to what I have described above, then we recommend giving this one from Doosl a try based on our experience with it.

Recommended.

Go for it.t how well it performed. My statements here reflect that testing.
